es, libel and naturalization law, Scout handbooks, and success manuals, James B. Salazar uncovers how the cultural practices of representing character operated in tandem with the character-building strategies of social reformers. His innovative reading of this archive offers a radical revision of this defining category in U.S. literature and culture, arguing that character was the keystone of a cultural politics of embodiment, a politics that played a critical role in determining-and contesting-the social mobility, political authority, and cultural meaning of the raced and gendered body.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCharacter in literature. 0aCharacterxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aBodies. 4aStates. 4aUnited. 4acategory. 4acentury. 4acharacter. 4acharting. 4aconcept. 4aculture. 4acultures. 4adevelopment. 4aearly-twentieth. 4afictional. 4afrom. 4agenres. 4aliterature. 4amid-nineteenth. 4amovements. 4anineteenth-century. 4apivotal. 4apolitical. 4areconceives. 4areform. 4asocial. 4athis. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814786536423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814786536.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aE